entry.title: Self-Driving Finding Lanes
entry.summary:
When design a self-driving car, we need to train the car to perceive what's around it. One of the most important environment factor are lane lines. All the following features could be useful in the identification of lane lines on the road:

- Color¶

- Shape¶

- Orientation¶

- Position in the image¶

1 Identify Lane Lines by Color¶

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>When design a self-driving car, we need to train the car to perceive what's around it. One of the most important environment factor are lane lines. All the following features could be useful in the identification of lane lines on the road:</p>
<h4 id="--Color">- Color<a class="anchor-link" href="#--Color">¶</a></h4><h4 id="--Shape">- Shape<a class="anchor-link" href="#--Shape">¶</a></h4><h4 id="--Orientation">- Orientation<a class="anchor-link" href="#--Orientation">¶</a></h4><h4 id="--Position-in-the-image">- Position in the image<a class="anchor-link" href="#--Position-in-the-image">¶</a></h4>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h4 id="1-Identify-Lane-Lines-by-Color">1 Identify Lane Lines by Color<a class="anchor-link" href="#1-Identify-Lane-Lines-by-Color">¶</a></h4><p>In red + green + blue [R, G, B] system, 0 is the darkest and 255 is the lightest. So white would be (255, 255, 255). Let’s code up a simple color selection in Python.</p>
<ul>
<li>1.1 First, I import pyplot and image from matplotlib. I also import numpy for operating on the image.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [1]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.image</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">mpimg</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">numpy</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">np</span>
<span class="o">%</span><span class="k">matplotlib</span> inline
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>1.2 then read in an image and print out some stats. I’ll grab the x and y sizes and make a copy of the image to work with. NOTE: Always make a copy of arrays or other variables in Python. If instead, you say "a = b" then all changes you make to "a" will be reflected in "b" as well!</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [7]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Read in the image and print out some stats</span>
<span class="n">image</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mpimg</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">imread</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'/home/isaac/Dropbox/SDC/img/test.jpg'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'This image is: '</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="nb">type</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">image</span><span class="p">),</span> 
         <span class="s1">'with dimensions:'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">image</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area">
<div class="prompt"></div>
<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>This image is:  <class 'numpy.ndarray'> with dimensions: (540, 960, 3)
</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [9]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Grab the x and y size and make a copy of the image</span>
<span class="n">ysize</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">image</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">xsize</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">image</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="c1"># Note: always make a copy rather than simply using "="</span>
<span class="n">color_select</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">image</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>1.3 Next I define a color threshold in the variables red_threshold, green_threshold, and blue_threshold and populate rgb_threshold with these values. This vector contains the minimum values for red, green, and blue (R,G,B) that I will allow in my selection.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [10]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Define our color selection criteria</span>
<span class="c1"># Note: if you run this code, you'll find these are not sensible values!!</span>
<span class="c1"># But you'll get a chance to play with them soon in a quiz</span>
<span class="n">red_threshold</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
<span class="n">green_threshold</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
<span class="n">blue_threshold</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
<span class="n">rgb_threshold</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">red_threshold</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">green_threshold</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">blue_threshold</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>1.4 Next, I'll select any pixels below the threshold and set them to zero. After that, all pixels that meet my color criterion (those above the threshold) will be retained, and those that do not (below the threshold) will be blacked out.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [11]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Identify pixels below the threshold</span>
<span class="n">thresholds</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">image</span><span class="p">[:,:,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o"><</span> <span class="n">rgb_threshold</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span> \
            <span class="o">|</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">image</span><span class="p">[:,:,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o"><</span> <span class="n">rgb_threshold</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">])</span> \
            <span class="o">|</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">image</span><span class="p">[:,:,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o"><</span> <span class="n">rgb_threshold</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">color_select</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">thresholds</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Display the image                 </span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">imshow</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">color_select</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The result, color_select, is an image in which pixels that were above the threshold have been retained, and pixels below the threshold have been blacked out.</p>
<p>In the code snippet above, red_threshold, green_threshold and blue_threshold are all set to 0, which implies all pixels will be included in the selection.</p>
<p>I will modify the values of red_threshold, green_threshold and blue_threshold until you retain as much of the lane lines as possible while dropping everything else. Your output image should look like the one below.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [14]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">color_select_2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">image</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1">#update the threshold</span>
<span class="n">red_threshold</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">200</span>
<span class="n">green_threshold</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">200</span>
<span class="n">blue_threshold</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">200</span>
<span class="n">rgb_threshold</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">red_threshold</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">green_threshold</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">blue_threshold</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Identify pixels below the threshold</span>

<span class="n">color_select_2</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">thresholds</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h4 id="2-Region-Masking">2 Region Masking<a class="anchor-link" href="#2-Region-Masking">¶</a></h4><p>At this point, however, it would still be tricky to extract the exact lines automatically, because we still have some other objects detected around the periphery that aren't lane lines. In this case, I'll assume that the front facing camera that took the image is mounted in a fixed position on the car, such that the lane lines will always appear in the same general region of the image. Next, I'll take advantage of this by adding a criterion to only consider pixels for color selection in the region where we expect to find the lane lines.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [51]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">region_select</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">image</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Define a triangle region of interest</span>
<span class="c1"># the origin (0,0) is in the upper left in image processing</span>
<span class="n">left_bottom</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">180</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">500</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">right_bottom</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">800</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">540</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">apex</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">480</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">320</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [52]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Linear fit (y = Ax + B) to identify the 3 sided region of interest</span>
<span class="c1"># np.polyfit() returns the coefficients [A, B] of the fit</span>
<span class="n">fit_left</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">polyfit</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">left_bottom</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">apex</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">left_bottom</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">apex</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">fit_right</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">polyfit</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">right_bottom</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">apex</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">right_bottom</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">apex</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">fit_bottom</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">polyfit</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">right_bottom</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">left_bottom</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">right_bottom</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">left_bottom</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [53]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Find the region inside the lines</span>
<span class="n">XX</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">YY</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">meshgrid</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">xsize</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ysize</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">region_threshold</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">YY</span> <span class="o">></span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">XX</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">fit_left</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">fit_left</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]))</span> <span class="o">&</span> \
                   <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">YY</span> <span class="o">></span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">XX</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">fit_right</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">fit_right</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]))</span> <span class="o">&</span> \
                   <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">YY</span> <span class="o"><</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">XX</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">fit_bottom</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">fit_bottom</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]))</span>
<span class="n">region_select</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">region_threshold</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">255</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [54]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">imshow</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">region_select</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<h4 id="Finding-Lines-of-Any-Color">Finding Lines of Any Color<a class="anchor-link" href="#Finding-Lines-of-Any-Color">¶</a></h4><p>As it happens, lane lines are not always the same color, and even lines of the same color under different lighting conditions (day, night, etc) may fail to be detected by our simple color selection.
What we need is to take our algorithm to the next level to detect lines of any color using sophisticated computer vision methods.
So, what is computer vision?</p>
